Subject: process: inject DXVK_HDR=0 / PROTON_ENABLE_HDR=0 when client is SDR

Diagnosis (from a focused investigation, see notes in patch body):

On KDE Plasma 6 / Wayland + Mesa 26.1 RADV, kwin advertises HDR Wayland
protocols (wp_color_manager_v1, frog_color_management_factory_v1)
GLOBALLY — not per-output. Mesa's Vulkan WSI honours them and reports
VK_COLOR_SPACE_HDR10_ST2084_EXT in vkGetPhysicalDeviceSurfaceFormatsKHR.
DXVK reads that list and exposes HDR availability to D3D11/12 games.

Apollo's per-output SDR signalling (EVDI EDID without CEA HDR extension,
display_evdi_t::is_hdr returning false, VDISPLAY::getDisplayHDRByName
returning false) is invisible to that path. So a game like Ghost of
Tsushima, running through Proton/DXVK, sees HDR available, enables its
HDR rendering path, tonemaps back to SDR poorly, and looks "too dark"
when the user disables HDR in-game.

Apollo can't change kwin's global advertisement, but it CAN tell the
spawned game itself to disable HDR via the documented DXVK / Proton env
vars. process.cpp already builds an `_env` map that feeds the child
process. We add two lines: when `launch_session->enable_hdr` is false
(client requested SDR), set `DXVK_HDR=0` and `PROTON_ENABLE_HDR=0`
unless the user already set them via apps.json's env block.

Result: a Steam Deck (no HDR panel) streaming an SDR session gets a
fully-SDR game pipeline, end to end. Apollo's encoder already emits
SDR pixels — this patch just makes the game itself not render in HDR
in the first place.

Note: this does NOT fix games with broken native SDR gamma curves
(Tsushima is documented to be broken even on Windows/PS5 SDR). For
those, the user needs in-game brightness adjustment or a Nexus
brightness-fix mod. But this patch removes one independent cause of
"dark stream" reports.

--- a/src/process.cpp
+++ b/src/process.cpp
@@ -415,6 +415,28 @@
     _env["APOLLO_CLIENT_SCALE_FACTOR"] = std::to_string(scale_factor);
     _env["APOLLO_CLIENT_FPS"] = fps_str;
     _env["APOLLO_CLIENT_HDR"] = launch_session->enable_hdr ? "true" : "false";
+
+    // When the client requested SDR, hint the Linux Vulkan / DXVK / Proton
+    // stack to disable HDR output. Without this, kwin_wayland's global
+    // wp_color_manager_v1 advertises HDR colorspaces; mesa RADV's WSI
+    // honours them and DXVK reports VK_COLOR_SPACE_HDR10_ST2084_EXT as
+    // available; games (e.g. Ghost of Tsushima) then enable their HDR
+    // rendering path and the resulting tonemap-back-to-SDR over the
+    // moonlight wire looks wrong (too dark / washed out). Apollo's encoder
+    // is already in SDR mode here (see video_colorspace.cpp), so forcing
+    // the game itself into SDR keeps the whole pipeline consistent.
+    //
+    // Only set when not already set by the user (per-app or global env in
+    // apps.json) — an explicit user override always wins.
+    if (!launch_session->enable_hdr) {
+      if (_env.find("DXVK_HDR") == _env.end()) {
+        _env["DXVK_HDR"] = "0";
+      }
+      if (_env.find("PROTON_ENABLE_HDR") == _env.end()) {
+        _env["PROTON_ENABLE_HDR"] = "0";
+      }
+    }
+
     _env["APOLLO_CLIENT_GCMAP"] = std::to_string(launch_session->gcmap);
     _env["APOLLO_CLIENT_HOST_AUDIO"] = launch_session->host_audio ? "true" : "false";
     _env["APOLLO_CLIENT_ENABLE_SOPS"] = launch_session->enable_sops ? "true" : "false";
